Mostly, I wanted to shake this piece out so I could move on. I'm certain I was not as fair or even handed as I could have been, but I think being fair and even-handed are qualities that are still just slightly out of my reach. I hope to do better next time. I know I will.

So finally, w/the release of HFW, I wrote like 2600 words about both games. Some complaints are legitimate, some are a little too mean. I spent a chunk focused on the story/the writing because it was irking me so bad even though I believe that those things aren't so important

I ended up just really ragging on it. I tried to write the piece like six separate times in that span, I would go back and edit, I'd try different angles of approach. I didn't want to just shit all over it because that's not productive.

Horizon is a franchise i've been grappling with for like 5 years. Zero Dawn was so uniquely bad to me that I felt I had to write something about it in order to flesh out and identify my own sensibilities - what makes a game good, what is successful design, etc
i finished a piece on horizon forbidden west. i should probably qualify some things as i post it.

Suffice to say. Nothing gets my motor going like calling a film Heat but it being all blue. Like calling a film Cold Point and it being all Orange. Makes my stupid ass go "Whoop!"

Deniro and Pacino = Cold Crime, Hot Justice. Again, two immutable concepts that are mutually exclusive. There is no Justice without Crime. No Crime without Justice. This has gotten so stupid. But sometimes the stupidest ideas are also the truest.

Heat = Orange, Cool = Blue. Two ideas that must coexist to exist and are in constant contest with each other. Robert Deniro: "I only want to get out of doing crime, which is why I must continue doing crime, which is what I really want."

Heat the film is maybe about denying the obvious truth of who you are/what you desire (a criminal/to commit crimes) by sublimating those desires within socially expressible concepts like family, security, freedom and this is illustrated by the film HEAT having Cool Color Palette.

Heat by all means is somewhat goofy and I understand why some people really don't like it, but something activates in my caveman brain when you call a movie HEAT and it's all blue. Heat is orange or red, Heat is not cool blue unless its so so hot. https://t.co/zyB7XIEAu5

The machines bring him back to life in this horrifying, painful sequence. You see his eyes being lasered back on by a metal tentacle for maybe three seconds while he shrieks in pain and I’m still thinking about it. The layers to it.

Also in The Matrix 4, the idea that neo’s story was weaponized against him, rendered futile, deeply trivialized. The shock and sadness of that revelation is insanely potent. “They turned my life into a video game” - absolutely knotted me up and made me want to cry.

I went to the eye doctor for the first time in a few years last Saturday - went without insurance- and wouldn’t you know that two frames with blue light blockers and verilite™️ coating cost me the same as a brand new Xbox. Granted, they’re cool frames, but holy fuck it was mad$$$
https://t.co/zPGc6CKQkV

Wild how much things can change even over the course of a single console generation. Wild how much things changed over the course of the gen after that (2014-2020). I wonder how much things will change between now and the next gen.
Playing bioshock late at night on the really nice tv at the house my mom would dog-sit at for extra money in the summer. Somehow beating it even though i thought it was terrifying.

Nights spent playing rock band 2 and 3 at parties. Telling labmates in my 9th grade biology class about how cool I thought dead rising was and how I couldn’t stop playing it. Remembering how a GameStop employee sold me on the first assassin’s creed. “It’s a game for gamers” lol

I remember staying up until 4AM marathoning Brütal Legend the night it launched. Going to the midnight release (when those were still happening) of Skyrim, Red Dead Redemption, Max Payne 3. Borrowing the Witcher 2 from a friend at the start of college.

I remember playing the OG borderlands during a pretty severe blizzard. I remember GTA IV/Halo 3 online with friends after school in 2008. Assassin’s creed 2 devoured my summer months after it came out.

Being able to look back at my dumb gamer history allows me to slot some things more easily. I remember the first relatively serious (for high school I guess) girlfriend I had was around when The Orange Box came out. We’d talk on the phone while I played TF2.

My sense of time (when things have taken place, the distance between events, what year something happened/what age I was when something happened) is maybe like a degree worse than your average person’s. Most of the past is like soup to me. Can name ingredients but not quantities.

Last game I ever logged in to play was Battleblock Theater. Super fun couch co-op game from the people that made castle crashers and Alien Hominid. I played it on my OG Xbox 360 in my first ever apartment at like 19? 20?

Most played games (from what I can sus) are TES IV: Oblivion, Saints row the third, Brothers in Arms: Hell’s Highway, Fallout 3, Far Cry 3, GTA IV, Assassin’s Creed 2, Halo 3, Fable 2/3 and Crackdown. What a time capsule.

Maybe it’s time to delete.

I think that’s healthier.  
The brain forgets some faces. The brain idly wonders about mostly forgotten friends and acquaintances. You don’t fixate or search to satisfy the curiosity. You just sit with it.

I don’t think there’s been a time in my life where I was passingly reminded of somebody and I haven’t been able to find out what they’re up to. 20 years ago if you thought of somebody from your life from an era bygone you had to just wonder about them and move on.

It’s dumb that it strikes me just now, scrolling through this rotted, desiccated site how incredibly profane it is. I should never have been able to see what someone I worked with 10 years ago is up to now. How they’ve changed, are they married, are they crazy or lonely etc.

Scrolled upon two people I know who are dead with still active facebook profiles. Kind of a joke somehow. I stumbled onto facebook’s memorialization settings a few days ago - eg what will happen to your profile when you die? Do you want it deleted? Do you want it to stay?

Weird bc I realized that without the reminder fb provides of certain people’s existences they kinda get memory holed. Here’s two hot topic coworkers I haven’t seen in 7 years, deactivated, gone. Here’s some middle school friends who’ve deactivated. What do they look like? Idr.

Thought randomly of this person I went to college with and was scrolling my fb friends to see if I could find them (name changed and idr what to) and found that like, 50 something friends on there have deactivated. I ended up clearing them out (very easy to do so)

I know I’m cherry picking a little here but it’s just been popping up in my feed here and there and it’s a little bewildering because I’ve found the game easy to parse and well designed. Not sure why I’ve been seeing so much criticism of this ilk recently.

I just read a polygon article titled “11 things RETURNAL doesn’t tell you” with one of the examples being the stone wall puzzles - which are effectively tutorialized in the first 5 min of gameplay. half of the tips in this article are things the game directly explains to you. https://t.co/oNNXKQdjZi

-instead of a Design Decision. The game opens with a little text crawl that says “dying is essential to the experience,” and that there is essentially no traditional save system for the sake of the design’s integrity

A critic I follow has been posting for the past three days or so about how this game should’ve been in early access because it lacks a traditional save feature “and that’s something they would’ve caught.” Implying the lack of a save system was a major design oversight-

So is it just me or is most of the media coverage of Returnal weirdly condescending w/a negative bent? The Cauldron dungeons are so exquisitely crafted, tightly designed slices of gameplay, it almost makes me wish the game was just more of that instead of it feeling like Ubisoft/Bioware tried to tack a story onto ARK

You can only fast travel if you have these fast travel packs? Which are a resource you expend to fast travel. They’re not exactly hard to come by in my experience but like, every other game just *lets* you fast travel. Why reinvent the wheel on that one? Doesn’t service the game.

The world is so cool but the writing is hokey as fuck and the acting is wooden. Everybody in HZD is stiff and lacking charisma. I don’t care about anything anybody says because it’s largely expository and it feels like the actors don’t even care about it.

The world is so big that walking everywhere isn’t really that viable but you end up spending most of your playtime on foot anyway because it’s too much of a pain to hold on to a mount for any stretch of time.

It does that thing a lot of AAA games are guilty of where it locks essential features into a skill tree - you can’t summon a mount unless you pour 9 skill pts into the mount branch. Otherwise you have to find/tame one, only to lose it if you wander too far away from it.

Crafting feels pointless because I’m never really running low on anything. The stealth is broken in that enemies see me from what feels like miles away and breaking line of sight doesn’t consistently work how it should. Giving me 10 weapons and four weapon slots kinda sucks.

I’m giving Horizon Zero Dawn a second chance (it came out in such close proximity to BOTW that I feel like maybe I didn’t judge it fairly the first time) but uh, I’m still finding it kind of really tedious in the Ubisoft way. Too many systems with not enough polish on them all.
